In [7]:
#removing columns with too many null values and with too many categories
df2 = df.drop(columns = ['emp_title', 'emp_length', 'annual_income_joint', 'verification_income_joint', 'debt_to_income_joint',
                        'months_since_last_delinq', 'months_since_90d_late', 'months_since_last_credit_inquiry',
                        'num_accounts_120d_past_due', 'state', 'sub_grade'])

In above cells, I removed all the columns with too many null values and also the columns with too many categories, because some machine learning algortihms required to convert data into numeric and columns with too many categories can make the data messy in this case.

df2['debt_to_income'].hist();

In [9]:
#filling null values with median value of debt to income
df2['debt_to_income'].fillna(df['debt_to_income'].median(), inplace = True)
Generate a minimum of 5 unique visualizations using the data and write a brief description of your observations. Additionally, all attempts should be made to make the visualizations visually appealing.¶

Since I have to predict the interest_rate columns, so all visualization will be related to the relation of interest_rate with other predictors.

In [10]:
#plotting relation between interest_rate and paid_interes
sns.set_style("darkgrid")
plt.figure(figsize = (10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x = "paid_interest", y = "interest_rate", data = df2, hue = "grade")
plt.title("Relation between Interest Rate and Paid Interest by Grade", fontsize = 16)
plt.xlabel("Paid_interest", fontsize = 13)
plt.ylabel("Interest_rate", fontsize = 13)
plt.show()

From above plot, it can be observed that there is a positive relation between Paid interest and Interest Rate as the value of Interest Rate increased with increase in Paid Interest. The plot shows that for Grade A, the value of paid interest and interest rate is lowest followed by grade B, C and D. The plot also shows that for grade G the value of interest rate and paid interest is highest followed by grade F and grade E.

In [11]:
#plotting relation between interest rate and homeowner ship

plt.ylabel("Interest_rate", fontsize = 13)
plt.show()

From above plot, it can be observed that the average value of interest rate is lowest for MORTGAGE type homeownership followed by OWN homeowner shipt. The plot shows that the interest rate is highest for RENT homeownership. There are outliers with pretty high value of Interest rate for all MORTGAGE, RENT, OWN type homeownership.

Most of the Not veriefied observations also have Interst rate values between 5 to almost 13. For overall interest rate there are many outliers with pretty extreme values between 25 to 32 too.

After selecting the features set, now I will convert all categorical variable into numerical by dummy variable technique and then will split the data into train and test data. The training data will be used for fitting the model and testing data will be used for checking the performance of the model.

In [18]:
#converting categorical variables into numerical variables
df2_num = pd.get_dummies(df2, drop_first = True)
#separating input and output features
X = df2_num.drop(columns = "interest_rate")
y = df["interest_rate"]
In [19]:
#splitting data into train and test data
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.3, random_state = 42)

Describe any data cleansing that must be performed and analysis when examining the data. Visualize the test results and propose enhancements to the model, what would you do if you had more time. Also describe assumptions you made and your approach.¶

Since the mean squared error for Linear Regression model is lower as compare to the Random Forest Regressor, so I concluded that the Linear regression model fits and genralize well to the data and perform better as compare to the Random Forest Regressor and can be used for making prdictions in future. Now, I will visualize the actual vs predicted values for linear regression model.

If I had more time, I would have tried more and more models to find an optimal model. I would have tuned the hyperparameters of different models to increase the performance of the model. I would have explored the relation of all features with interest rate and would have used only those predictors that have significant relation with interest rate. There are few assumptions for my final model that the residuals are normally distrubited, the linearity of the data and homegenity of variance in the data.
